SIMPLE: integrate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Integrate
<hw>In"te*grate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Integrated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Integrating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>integratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>integrare</ets> to make whole,
renew: cf. F. <ets>int⟦eacute⟧grer</ets>. See <er>Integer</er>,
<er>Entire</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To form into one whole; to make entire; to complete;
to renew; to restore; to perfect.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧That conquest rounded and
<xex>integrated</xex> the glorious empire.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>De
Quincey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two distinct substances, the soul and body, go to compound and
<qex>integrate</qex> the man.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To indicate the whole of; to give the sum or total
of; <as>as, an <ex>integrating</ex> anemometer, one that indicates or
registers the entire action of the wind in a given time</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>To subject to the operation of
integration; to find the integral of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>integrated</ent>⟦br⟧
